                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>The following documents relate to the foreign policy aspects of the problem of
                    the requirements of Section 22 of the Agricultural Adjustment Act of 1933, as
                    amended (Act of July 3, 1948, 62 Stat. 1247) vis-à-vis the international
                    obligations of the United States under the General Agreement on Tariffs and
                    Trade (<gloss target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss>). The first documents, which
                    antedate the year 1951, describe the elements and purpose of the Section 22
                    provisions and the foreign economic policy questions raised by it. The latter
                    documents focus on the legislation of 1951 and on a specific diplomatic <hi
                        rend="italic">démarche</hi> made to the United States Government by one of
                    the Contracting Parties to <gloss target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss>, apprehensive
                    of prospective Section 22 action by the United States.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
